{"/service/ndnp/au/batch_au_flagg_ver01/data/sn85038485/00340583814/1908030801/0113.xml":{"full_text":"(STOCK MARKET IS\nf Z _ j DULL\n\nDistinguishing Features for\nSeveral Weeks\nSTREET IS WAKING UP\nRealizes at Last That Politicians Mean\nBusiness and Something Must Be\nDone\u2014Business Outlook Is\nStill Gloomy.\nn\na\nrli n\nhet BY W. G. NICHOLAS.\n>f Tori, March 7.\u2014(.Special.)\u2014Thin\nDIO\nIn todecl\u00bb nervous, narrow and dull ato\nga. characteristics of the stock market.\npo< 'se have been the distinguishing feat\nw s for several weeks, and the promise\nj a change cannot be called emcourag\nori The disturbing factor is the attitude\n\u00a7r% 'the political parties towards eorpora\n\u20acr\u00abWns and towards speculation. It is idle i\nthink otherwise or to say otherwise.\nBi|ithing better illustrates and reveals the\nym pertainty in men\u2019s minds than the stock\nep. trket at this moment.\n|r Capital is stubbornly holding back and\nusing to lend aid to any kind of en\n3 prise or development una.il a better\n\u2022eeight of the political and business lu\nt e can be had. The two are so inex\n1 Icably interwoven that they go together,\nf .'here has probably never been a time\nJien politics and business were more\nclosely interdependent than now. This\nview may be disputed by some, but the\nltacts are there. A great army ot inves\nItltors feel that it is almost Ijke buying\nA*nn> a lawsuit tu put their money into\nprporation securities, wit'll the federal\n1 ad state governments and legislatures\nrrayed in open hostility, ami with the\ny.jtopulace apparently inflamed to the en\nouragement of any and every sort of as\nault on substantial Interests.\nWhile dull and almost enemic, the stock\nnarket cannot be described as apathetic.\n>n the contraiy the prevailing sentiment\nis one of intensity of Interest with a back\nground of timidity and fear as to what\n/may be ahead. At the prevailing low\nApnces few people are selling unless\nHobliged to, and with the surrounding and\nfever present uncertainty, few people care\n\u2018to buy or make new commitments. The\nPsituation is in the highest degree unsat\nisfactory for everybody.\nI Not the least disquieting feature is the\ni.discovery which Wall street is making\ni hat a vast majority of people are tak\n1 \\g the White House view, that the un\nerlying cause of the business appreher.\nion, and of the panic which preceded U,\nl.ere caused by over-speculation in the\nf ock market, and by the misdeeds of high\n\u2018kanciers and those entrusted with the\n8 anagement of great corporate interests.\nds overwhelming sentiment finds ex\nI ession in the campaigns at Washington\n\u2018d almost every state capital lor the\n.oppression of gambling in stocks and\narm commodities.\nit took Wall street a long time to realize\n.chat there was anything in this move-\nment beyond the mere, idle crusading of\n(demagogic politicians striving to gain the\ngood will of the peanut galleries. That j\n1 )t means a general movement, represent\ning a tremendous majority of the people, Is\nnow dawning upon the rank and tile of\nthe financial district. The revelation is a\nshock as well as a surprise. It lias shaken\nthe dull provincialism of the street from\ncircumference to center. It spells to the\nawakened Wall street a great popular,\nindorsement of the President and h.s\n\u2019policies.\u201d\ni The talkers and the wise-acres of tne\ni jstreet had deluded themselves into the\ni\u00abhef that the country had very generally\naccepted the theory that the administra\ntion was chiefly responsible for the panic\nand its after effects; whereas, the weight\nof testimony is coming in directly the\nI other way at this writing. Whether or\nnot there will be a change remains to be\n8eFor the present, however, the street\nfinds itself up against the proposition that\nit is the under dog in the tight, and that\nvi is In for a further process of disciplin\ning. To Wall street it seems incredible\nthat any considerable portion of the bank\ni ing population could take any other posi\nvtion than that Injury to Wall street is\ninjury to the entire material interests of\nSAW MILL MAN\nUP AGAINST\nTIE ALCOHOLIC BUZZ SAW CAME\nSquandered Fifteen Thousand\u2014Tells\nHow He Wasted Ills Entire\nEarning* in Dissipation.\nCiiarles B. James, care Janies Sanato\nrium, Memphis. Tenn.\nDear Sir ami Friend\u2014I am pleased\nto say to you that, although L had bee i\nj drinking hard for ten years and had\nlittle or no confidence as to the cura\ntive properties of your remedies, yet l\nam now glad to say to you that I am\nentirely free from all desire for alco\nholic stimulants of any arid every kind.\n1 am a band sawyer by trade and have\ncommanded as high a salary as any\nman in my state, viz; $7.50 per day,\nand should have been worth at least\n$15,000. having earned in the past ten\nyears $23,400. But as a matter of fact,\n1 had wasted my entire earnings in\ndissipation. Fortunately for me my\n-employers, Brodey Lumber company.\nI of this city, thought enough of me to\n4 insist on my going to you for relief,\nr,\\ and on leaving you my job with them\ni was still open to me. 1 take pleasure\nJin recommending your Sanatorium to\n(fall who need treatment and who are\nearnestly seeking relief. With best\n|regards to all connected with the Han\nJ fatorium, X am your friend,\nGEORGE NUTT.\nf Warren, Ark., January 13, 1006.\nT\nFKF.E DRUG CURE,\npi Chas. B. James, 3 33 Poplar Are.,\nft Dept,. 23, Memphis, Tenn. Please send\nto my address, all charges paid, a\nfree trial bottle for patient using\n(state here number of grains used\n.each 24 hours) grains of\nl (state kind of drug here)\nI State here if used by mouth or\nhypodermically\nI A Name\nTown State\nNearest Express Oftice\n,S.\nI JAMES HOME (THE REMEDIES\n;>r Drug Addictions, Alcoholism, To\nil icco and Cigarette Habits, Nervous-\njas and Insomnia, will be furnished\nthe following prices:\nHilsky, Wine or Beer .$12.50\nI Ibacco, Cigarette or Snuff. 5.00\n1 forms of Nervousness or Jn\nH a omnia 1.00\nK prices for Hypodermic or Internal\nHH'* >9 Treatment for Drug Addictions\nWM i finished on application, with\n!E l18 pinple treatment. Express\nif. i. a when requested.\nI ,T^ toug Addict inns I n unb\nI S'LtVhii kiMi t igarette\nV ,'rt_w,th h m testimonials, etc),\nliij He has option cover. ('orr*\u00bbs-\\\nI O^TTC*O!^Kill^ IrfOres.-- j'harles\nI m Alamo a tor inm. 133 1\nbftn23, Memphis, I\nSL\nthe country, and that assaults on capital\nare suicidal to labor and to every kind\nof enterprise\u2014suicidal and murderous.\nTo the utter disguset of the street,\nknowledge is forced upon it that most\npeople regard that especial locality os a\nden of thieves that might be entirely\ni eliminated without doing the country any\nj harm The population of the street knows\nI differently, but that does no make any\ndifference. Protests and angry arguments\ntall on deaf outside ears to all seeming.\nHeretofore. Watt street has been sneer\ningly indifferent to any and all hostile\nlegislation looking to regulation of its\nmethods. It has been a law unto itself,\neven as the stock exchange is. Not only\nindifferent, but callous to outside criti\ncism. Throughout a long series of years\nthe New York stock exchange has re\nfused to recognize such a thing as the\npossibility of legislation which would in\nterfere with its affairs. It is a non-incor\nporated association of 1000 men wlio have\ntheir rules for their own government,\nsome of them within the law and sonic\nof them being entirely for the personal\nconvenience and comfort of those on the\ninside and regardless of the rights of the\npublic.\nThis has been notably illustrated in\nthe non-enforcement of the requirements\ncalling for reports of corporations Whose\nstocks are dealt in on the exchange. There\nare many stocks bought and sold on the\nNew York stock exchange about which\nthe public has no reliable information,\nand which could and should be thrown\noff, simply because the managements\nscornfully refuse to make public their\nfinancial condition as required by law.\nThe exchange is in the early stages of ;t\nrude awakening on this and many other\npoints about which they have been wil\nfully neglectful of their duties to the pub\nlic. from whom patronage ia asked and\nobtained.\nThe Hepburn bill and other measures In\nCongress and equally drastic proposi\ntions before the New' York and other\nstate legislatures, distasteful as they are,\nmust be beneflciently educational to \"V\\ all\nstreet.\nThe loud proclamation made that\nnone of these obnoxious measures can\nbe passed, but that is merely whistling\nagainst the wind. The great truth is\ndawning upon the oracles that their more\nsaying so does not make it so, and the\nstreet is in a stale of genuine alarm lest\nit be put out of business or seriously\nembarrassed. Measures are at last be\ning taken by the Stock Exchange to\ncombat hostile legislative action. The wise\nmen of that body are preparing to de\nscepd upon the ignorant statesmen at\nWashington and Albany and show them\nwherein they are weak, deluded victims\nof grossly ignorant prejudices. What suc\ncess these illuminating efforts will have,\nis a subject of earnest discussion.\nOne trouble with Wall street is that\nit does not know anything about what\nIs going on. or thought or talked of,\noutside of the immediate sphere of New\nYork influence, say within a radius of 25\nmiles from the city hall. Anything that\nwill enlightep or quicken the intelligence\nof the denizens of the street will be\ndistinctly beneficial.\nSome of the literature that is now\ncoming out on the subject of the Hep\nburn bill and other measures of kindred\ntemper is laughable. It is quite the com\nmon thing for members of the exchange\nto describe the Hepburn bill as \u201cassin\nine,\u201d \u201cidiotic,\u201d \u201ccrazy,\u201d etc... and to at\ntempt to dismiss all apprehensions by\nloftily declaring that not a one of them\nhas the slightest chance on earth of ever\nbecoming a law, or if placed upon the\nstatute books to receive the approval\nof the courts.\nOf course all that sort of \u201cargument\u201d\nwill produce a profound impression on\nthe residents of Oklahoma. Mississippi,\nMinnesota and other states, where the\npeople have their feet on the soli, and\nwho think they know as much about\nbusiness and what is good for the coun\ntry as the biggest banker or broker in\nthe metropolis. For the moment Wall\nstreet, is a debating school on national\npolitics and on legislation affecting cor\nporations and progressive enterprise of\neven' description. Little else is talked\nabout and what speculation there is in\nthe stock market is largely dependent\nthereon.\nMeanwhile, railroad earnings are fall\ning off, as shown In the weekly and\nmonthly reports which are made by most\nof them. By comparison with a year\nago, the exhibits are startlingly depress\ning. The decrease in gross revenues,\nlarge though they are, make a good show\ning as against the net earnings. It has\nthus far been impossible for the trans\nportation companies to scale down their\noperating expenses and other expenditure\nin proportion to the decreased income.'\nTo make matters worse, they are seem\ningly afraid to enter upon a campaign\nfor a reduction in wages, the attitude of\ntho national administration deterring\nthem from such action. It is commonly\nbelieved that if business continues bad\nth\u00bb railroads will eventually be forced\nto a wholesale wage reduction, and that\nwhen such act becomes compulsory they\nwill move in concert.\nIt is observed in this connection that\nthe general business of the country, as\nreflected in the bank clearings, keeps\nclose pace with the diminution in rail\nroad earnings. The bank clearings for the\nmonth of February show a falling off\nof about 26 per cent compared with Feb\nruary, 1907, and about .10 per cent com\npared with 1906. Every industrial and\ncommercial item of a favorable sort is\nmade the most of, but the fact remains\nthat the general business situation is\nunsatisfactory. On every hand we hear\nof reductions in dividends or the passing\nof dividends and of the application of\nrigid economies.\nAs the volume of business contracts\nand less employment is found for live\nmoneV capital continues to pile up in the\nfinancial centers. Solvent borrowers are\nholding aloof because they cannot find\nsafe employment for borrowed funds at\na profit. The banks are looking about\nfor customers, but are obliged to dis\ncriminate. The mere fact that a man\nor an institution or a corporation wants\nto borrow at this period of general un\ncertainty of itself arouses suspicion as\nto the solvency or good judgment of the\napplicant.\nHence it is that railroads that are\nobliged to do any financing must pay al\nmost usurious rates for accommodations.\nThe bond houses and the banks are load\ned with bonds, for which there is no\nmarket, and in no quarter can it be\ntruthfully said that there are signs of\nsubstantial revival. This is a gloomy\npicture, but an accurate one.\nBefore leaving for Europe J. P. Mor\ngan let it be known that he had changed\nhis mind about standing behind Southern\nrailway. He had previously told those\ninterested in Its securities'that he would\nprovide such money as the system might\nhave to use during the season of de\npression.\nThe continued hostile attitude of the\nstates through which the road runs is\nmentioned as the chief reason for his\nchange of front. Another chief reason\nis probably the fact that the road needs\nmore money than at first estimated. Erie\nis also suffering sympathetically with\nSouthern because that, too, is classed as\none of the Morgan pets, which is water\nlogged by over-capitalization.\nThe tunnels under Manhattan island\nand connecting it with Long Island and\nNew Jersey will cost, when completed,\nnot less than $300,000,000. Already the\ntube construction has cost $200,000,000.\nWhen finished they will bring all the\nterritory immediately round-about Man\nhattan In close communication and will\nalmost annihilate distance, bringing\nthose who live 16 or 20 miles away al\nmost as close to the heart of the city as\nIf they resided as many blocks from\ntheir destination. It will be two or three\nyears before the great bulk of this\nenormous investment begins to yield an\nincome. Meantime the money has gone\nInto the projects on faith.\nSee Wm. Wise Co. price list.\nLL\u2014Small boarding\ncare Age-Herald, i\nI\nPensacola\u2019s Quickest Shipper. I\nENSACOLA, FLORIDA.\n2 Full Quarts.$1.75\n4 Full Quarts .$4.00 4 pull Quarts.3.15\ns IZ I\n12 Full Quarts.12.00 12 Fl111 Quarts.9 00\nExpress Paid. ExPre8S Paid*\n4 Full Quarts. $5.50\nI Express Paid.\n\u25a0jmfcii I\nI\ni 1\nI\n\nV\n12 4 1\ng p\"u If\nS-tj Quarts Quarts g E\n-\u2022a B 50\n$12.75. $50\u00b0\n0\u2019S\na p, Express Express g \u00a33\nm Paid. Paid-\nV\nA .j i 4\n\nI S\n\n\n\u00a7S 'a5M^HI\u00bb^^^S5j*yaajpr-~ jj-_* .y- \u2018if\u20184y\",v >/\u2018J MJpEB -\u2022*'V B t^/V\nI Express Paid. B\nI Special Prices \u00b0.ci ggP^Paid^ I\nI BAILEY\u2019S MALT, the kind your grandad liked, SLOO^11 $4.00 $6.60 $9.76 S\nI BILL BAILEY\u2019S Best Whiskey, the genuine article, 1,00 4.00 5.50 9.75 I\nI OLD ALF, a whiskey made to please and does it, .85 3.16 4.70 9.00 I\nI ROSE GIN, the Kidney Reliever, .75 3.00 4.50 9.00 1\ni MONOGRAM No. 11, K'auJaft^SJtSf'aiSrj.SS: 100 4.00 6.00 12.00 I\nI 0. K. GIN, a good article that you will like. .50 2.60 3.45 6.60\nI I TENNESSEE CORN WHISKEY. Mountain Made, .50 2.57 3.42 6.57 I\nI MOOG\u2019S APRICOT BRANDY, Fine and Dandy. .68 2.62 3.48 6.62 I\nI If You Can Beat These Prices and Goods, Your Money Back. 1\nI 4 uart, $375 WE GUARANTEE DELIVERY. 4 Fu\u201e QMrt!,.$2.00 I\nI 4 Express Paid3 75 QUICK SHIPMENTS. Express Collect. I\nI ___ _ J\nP*... fsanaBMM\u2014n 1 nil \u2014\u2014\u2014Mi\u2014ium\nCats a la Carte.\nThomas A. Janvier, In Harper's Maga\nzine for March.\nIf ever I take to innkeeping, I certain\nly shall charge for the use of cats not\nless than half a crown apiece a (lay;\nand I tlx that figure because it is what\nI am willing to pay for the use of a\nnice cat myself.\nOur little friend was attached to the\nMinerva In some confidential capacity\nthat I never uuite got to tile roots of.\nSuuib\u2014such was the gentle creature's\nmildly explosive name\u2014conceivably prac\ntised the profession that he was born to;\nbut his mousing\u2014If lie did mouse-was\nthe bast conspicuous of his employ\nments. All of his time\u2014until I asked for.\nand was permitted to have ,a share of\ntt\u2014seemed to be. passed at. ease In (lie\nbar-parlor; where a comfortably cush\nioned chair was reserved for him. and\nhis only duties seemed to be to cheer\nwith his affection the dignified Lady\nManager In Iter moments of loneliness,\n-i_.._- \u2014_\nand to display to the select frequenters\nof that littlle bibulous sanctuary his\nmany engaging parts. It is my belief,\nhowever, that his confidential duty\u2014a\nvery responsible and a very delicate\none\u2014was to indicate by his manner to\nward visitors any chance mistakes\nmade in admitting mere tap-room tip\nplers into that privileged privacy. In\nholding this belief I may be in error;\nbut I am well persuaded that I myself\ndid not become persona grata In the bar\nparlor until Squib\u2014by responding to my\near-tickling and jowl-rubbing advances\nby arching his black back and purring\nforth to me his trustful friendliness\u2014\nhad certified to my being versed in the\nliner customs of cat polite society; and\ntherefore necessarily qualified to asso\nciate with the higher, the bar-parlor,\nclasses of my own human kind.\nWithout much expecting that anything\nwould come of it, I said that 1 should be\nvery glad to have Squib sent up with\nour breakfast: explaining that petting a\ncat, and especially a black cat. gave a\nbright start to the darkest morning; and\npointing out that the mornings just then\n\u2014toward th# end of Noverabsr-*were the\n\n\ndarkest and disinalest of all the English\nyear. I have my doubts ps to the coin* j\nplete understanding of my explanation;\nbut the essential fact was clear that\u2014j\nus no doubt they expressed It\u2014the gen-\ntleman wanted to play with the cat: and\nhis infantile folly, of course, was no\nbody\u2019s business but his own. And so\nmy order for a cat for breakfast was\ntreated precisely as would have been\ntreated my order for buttered toast or\neggs and bacon\u2014excepting only that\nmy cat came up-stairs m the maid ser\nvant's arms, and went down again on\nhis own little black legs. Instead of\ncoming and going on a tray. Thereafter,\nwhen we came down to breakfast, we\nfound Squib engagingly stretched out on\nthe hearth-rug before the fire in our sit\nting-room: a truly heart-warming lit\ntle black object; and all the more heart\nwarming because of his eagerness to\npurr out to us his lit-tl\u00a9 morning song of\nlove.\nWm. Wise Co., Chattanooga,\nTenn.\nI v\nDO YOU KNOW WASHINGTON7\nAverage American Knows Only the\nBarest Facts About First President.\nOwen Ulster, In the Mnreh Everybody\u2019s.\nBorn February 22. 1732; died December\n14, 17M; fought Indians\u2014time and place\na little vague\u2014was he not with Braddock?\nMarried a widow named Martha; was\ncommander all through our Revolution;\nwas our first president; and had two\nterms; wrote a farewell address; knew\nLafayette and Thomas Jefferson; crossed\nthe Delav/are at Trenton Just before\nChristmas, and surprised the Hessians;\nbeat Cornwallis at Yorktown; and was\nfirst In, war. first In peace, and first In the\nhearts offhls countrymen.\nThese aVe all public facts. What does\nthe reader know of Washington the man?\nMore than likely it will be as follows:\nCut down a cherry-tree with a hatchet;\nowned up to having done so. saying, \u2019\u2019B'u\nther, X cannot tell a He\u201d; threw a stone\nyery tar across some river; climbed .up\nthe side of the natural bridge and cut hla\ninitials; worked hard at school, waa\nsteady; was very good all the time, and\neverybody Iboked up to him; of course,\nvery brave; of course, very wise, and a\ngreat patriot; was one of the greatest\nmen in all history; wus tall, strong, wore\nthose knee breeches of colonial days, and\na wig; looked stern; would probably lec\nture you, and tell you to be virtuous and\nyou would be happy. Such, If I mistake\nnot, is the reader\u2019s notion of Washing\nton as a man; cold, austere, unemotion\nal, without passions, grand, not merel/\ngreater than human, simply not human\nat all; a sort of marble statue. A figure\nto prize, to be proud of as an American,\na figure to revere, but not a character to\nlove, to be drawn to, to feel any kinship\nwith. In two words, immortal yet not\nliving.\nBlend A\u2014Four full quarts,\n100 proof rye, delivered in your\nhome, $3.50. Campbell-Burton\nCo,, Box 358, Memphis, Tenn.","height":"27788","width":"19956"}}
